article.description:
Adam Morrison scored 24 points to help No.
5 Gonzaga beat Santa Clara 85-71 on Saturday night for its 34th
consecutive home win, longest streak in the nation.
article.headline: Morrison drops 24 to help 'Zags extend home win streak
article.linkText: Morrison drops 24 to help 'Zags extend home win streak
article.story: SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- After four straight close wins, Gonzaga coach Mark Few was pleased his fifth-ranked Bulldogs put an opponent away early for once. Gonzaga beat Santa Clara 85-71 Saturday night, and led by 25 points midway throught the second half as it was never seriously challenged. "We had some real good streaks where we combined defense and offense and that provided us a gap," Few said after the Bulldogs won their 34th consecutive home game, the longest streak in the nation after Illinois' loss earlier in the day. "We haven't done a lot of that all year." Gonzaga (18-3, 8-0 West Coast Conference) has been surprisingly sluggish even as it remains undefeated in the league. The Bulldogs allowed Loyola Marymount, San Francisco, San Diego and Portland to stay competitive deep into the previous four games. "That was one of our best efforts of the year," said J.P. Batista, who had 21 points and seven rebounds for Gonzaga, breaking a streak of four consecutive double-doubles. Batista was 8-for-11 from the field. Adam Morrison, tops in the nation at 29 points per game, led all scorers with 24. Howver, he shot just 7-for-18. Sean Mallon added a season-high 15 points for Gonzaga, which won its ninth consecutive game and beat Santa Clara for the 12th straight time. The 34-game home winning streak tied the longest in team history. Santa Clara (8-12, 1-7) has lost seven straight, its longest streak since losing nine in a row in 1973-74. The Broncos, who are last in the WCC, shot only 43 percent -- including 4-for-17 on 3-pointers. Gonzaga shot just 46 percent in the game, but made 9-of-21 3s. The ragged game saw 52 fouls. Gonzaga, which leads the nation in free-throw shooting at 79 percent, was just 22-for-32 (68 percent). Santa Clara was 21-for-35. Mitch Henke led Santa Clara with 17 points, while Travis Niesen added 14. Santa Clara coach Dick Davey said this Gonzaga team is as good as any in recent years. "They're hard to guard," Davey said. "They've got great balance. They're very intelligent." Santa Clara started a freshman and two sophomores, but Davey refused to point to injuries and inexperience as an excuse. "We all have them," Davey said. "You have to go with what you have." Gonzaga took the lead early in the first half and never gave up control. The Zags led 12-8 before 3s by Erroll Knight, Morrison and Derek Raivio gave them a 21-13 lead. Gonzaga stretched the advantage to 34-22 behind a pair of hook shots by Batista and a steal and dunk by Jeremy Pargo. The Bulldogs led 48-32 at halftime after shooting 60 percent, including hitting six 3s. Santa Clara made 48 percent in the first, but only 2-for-10 on 3s. Morrison's 3 capped a 7-0 Gonzaga run for a 69-45 lead and the Zags coasted as they kept their record unblemished in the 2-year-old McCarthey Athletic Center. Raivio, who leads the nation in free throw shooting at 96 percent, made both his free throws Saturday and has now made 26 straight since Dec. 31. Gonzaga hosts Saint Mary's on Monday.
